## Migration: `Thread.Abort` → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Why this breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is gone (`SYSLIB0006`). The runtime no longer supports forcibly injecting exceptions into threads.

### Pattern identified: **Timeout enforcement**

Your code aborts a thread exceeding a time limit. The replacement uses `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` with `Task.Run`.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run + WaitAsync gives us a cancellable timeout.
            // The work delegate should accept and check the token
            // for prompt cooperative cancellation.
            return Task.Run(work, cts.Token)
                       .WaitAsync(cts.Token)    // .NET 6+ API
                       .GetAwaiter()
                       .GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Preferred overload — lets the work cooperate with cancellation
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        try
        {
            return Task.Run(() => work(token), token)
                       .WaitAsync(token)
                       .GetAwaiter()
                       .GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(work, token)` | Thread pool is more efficient; integrates with cancellation |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `.WaitAsync(token)` | Cancellable wait without blocking a thread; .NET 6+ API |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (implicit via timeout) | Cooperative — work must check the token |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed entirely | No equivalent needed; cancellation is voluntary |

### Critical pitfall: cancellation is cooperative

Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation **will not interrupt** work that doesn't check the token. If the `Func<T>` does long-running or blocking work, you must modify it:

```csharp
// ❌ BAD — ignores cancellation, runs to completion even after timeout
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => {
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
        Process(item);  // never checks token
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ✅ GOOD — checks token at each checkpoint
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token => {
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### Other pitfalls

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers if not disposed | Always wrap in `using` |
| Blocking I/O (`socket.Receive`, `Thread.Sleep`) ignores the token | Replace with async overloads or `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` |
| Swallowing `OperationCanceledException` silently | Only catch at the top-level orchestration point (as shown above) |
| Truly uncooperative code (third-party, native calls) | Move to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill` — this is the only way to forcibly stop uncooperative code in modern .NET |

### If you need an async version

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```
